—Oberösterreichisches Landesmuseum, Linz; 
Austria
;

Total DNA was extracted from one leg (

), dissected from the investigated individuals. Each dissected leg was placed in 2 mL microtubes filled with 1 mL of the specific digestion buffer (

) and incubated for 36 hours at 56 °C. The specific digestion buffer consisted of 5 mM CaCl2, 2% sodium dodecyl sulphate (SDS), 65 mM dithiothreitol (DTT), 450 μg/ml proteinase K, 150 mM Tris buffer pH 8 and 100 mM NaCl (

). The total DNA purification was performed using a phenol-chloroform extraction (UltrapureTM Phenol: Chloroform: Isoamyl Alcohol, ThermoFisher Scientific, Waltham, MA, 
USA
) (

). The obtained DNA was quantified using the spectrophotometer Infinite 200 PRO 
NanoQuantTM
(TECAN Life Technologies, Männedorf, 
Switzerland
) and stored at -20 °C until the analysis. As negative control, double-distilled Rnase-Dnasefree water was used for all of these processes.

The PCR was performed in 25 μl of volume using HotStarTaq Polymerase (Qiagen, Hilden, 
Germany
) following manufacturers’ instructions using 5 μl of DNA, forward and reverse probes (500 nM), as reported in 

. The PCR assay was performed on Applied Biosystems® 2720 Thermal Cycler (ThermoFisher Scientific) and sampled were amplified, after an initial activation at 95 °C for 15 min, through 35 cycles (1 min at 95 °C, 1 min at 40 °C, and 1.5 min at 72 °C), followed by a final extension at 72 °C for 7 min.All amplicons were visualized on a 1.5% agarose gel. The obtained amplicons were purified using ExoSAP-IT Express (ThermoFisher Scientific) and they were sequenced through the standard Sanger methodology. The obtained sequences were analyzed using BioEdit (

) to create the consensus one aligning forward and reverse sequences and BLAST (using megablast algorithm) (

). Specimens that were successfully barcoded and whose sequences are presented here are listed in 
Tab. 1
.

Obtained sequences were processed on MEGA11 software (

): DNA alignment was made with Clustal Alignment, neighbor-joining (NJ) phylogenetic analysis (

) was performed with bootstrap values determined from 10.000 replications (

), and intra- and interspecific distances were obtained using the model of Kimura 2-parameters (Kimura 1980). 

Ancistrocerus gazella
(Panzer)

was chosen to root the tree following the phylogeny proposed by 

, and three other European species of 

Stenodynerus

belonging to different species-groups were used as outgroups. The four sequences were downloaded from the Barcode of Life Data System.

